    <title>Combined summary - Packaged Transaction Relay</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T21:46:49.877582+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-June/020544.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The bitcoin-dev mailing list has seen several discussions on different topics related to Bitcoin transactions. One of the main issues discussed is stuck transactions resulting from the minimum fee rate policy, which has led to proposals for pre-signed transactions with low fee rates and packaged transaction relay models. The proposed objective of packaged transaction relay is to propagate transactions that are incentive-compatible to mine, even if they don't meet minimum feerate alone, while reducing orphaned transactions and minimizing packages. However, there is concern about potential bandwidth waste in nodes running with different policy rules, and ways to mitigate this are suggested. Overall, there is agreement to eliminate the need for headers and remove fee + weight information from pkginfo to reduce complexity.Another email thread discusses a proposal for packaged transaction relay that also aims to propagate incentive-compatible transactions for mining. The discussion centers around the implementation of sendaddrv2 messages and the version constraints associated with it. While BIP155 defines addrv2 and sendaddrv2 for all protocol versions, some implementations reject messages they don't know. As a courtesy, the messages are therefore not sent to nodes with a version before 70016. It is suggested that authors update BIP155 and BIP330, as well as any pending proposals that may have picked up this pattern from BIP155.Discussions also touched on the value of posting development ideas to the list vs using Github repositories and the BIP process, as well as the need for improved Bitcoin standards. One developer expressed concern about protocol being defined as a "courtesy" and questioned why certain comments were accepted instead of being specified properly within the Bitcoin Improvement Proposals (BIPs). The conversation also involved the issue of bandwidth waste due to different policy rules among nodes, dishonest peers announcing packages with false information, and the insufficiency of the initial protocol versioning design.In addition, another email thread discussed Bitcoin's P2P protocol versioning, which has been criticized for its complexity. The proposal suggests updating the versioning scheme to eliminate the requirement to consider any unknown message type as valid and to add versioning to individual protocols, reflecting the insufficiency of the initial protocol versioning design.Overall, the discussions highlighted the decentralized nature of the Bitcoin community and the importance of collaboration and transparency in making improvements to the protocol. There were also some disagreements and criticisms exchanged between participants, emphasizing the need for courtesy in public processes.</summary>
